"&#xa0;\nAFS0105Written evidence submitted by the CBI Response&#xa0;&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;&#xa0;The government’s decentralisation agenda is the right one – increased freedoms for teachers and school leaders supports the improvement of standards and educational outcomes.&#xa0;\nFor the programme to be successful in the long-term, schools need clear guardrails within which to work and deliver these improvements – and this includes strong governance and leadership, as well as smart accountability systems. Not enough attention has yet been paid to these guardrails.&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nAs the academies programme expands, it is important to consider the role of the ‘middle tier’ to guarantee standards and sustainability – but this cannot be an excuse to slide back into Local Authorities running schools.&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nDecember 2013\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n \nFirs\nt steps: A new approach for our schools\n, CBI, November 2012\n \nLeading the way: improving school governance and leadership, \nCBI, November 2013\n \nSchool autonomy and accountability: are they \nrelated to student performance?\n, OECD, October 2011\n \nWhat makes schools successful? Resources, policies and practices – Volume IV\n, OECD, 2013\n \nWhat makes schools successful? Resources, policies and practices – Volume IV\n, OECD, 2013\n \nThe framework for \nschool inspection\n, Ofsted, September 2012\n \nAccounting Officer Accountability System Statement for Education and Children’s Services\n, DfE, September 2012\n \nSchool Governance: Learning from the best\n, Ofsted, May 2011\n \nAccounting Officer Accountability Syst\nem Statement for Education and Children’s Services\n, DfE, September 2012\n \nAccounting Officer Accountability System Statement for Education and Children’s Services\n, DfE, September 2012\n"